{{Infobox language family |name = Piaroa–Saliban |altname = Saliban |region = [[Colombia]] and [[Venezuela]] |familycolor = American |fam1 = [[Jodï–Saliban languages|Jodï–Saliban]]? |glotto = sali1297 |glottorefname = Saliban |child1 = ''[[Saliba language|Saliva]]'' |child2 = [[Piaroa language|Piaroan]] |child3 = ? ''[[Hotï language|Hotï]]'' }}
The '''Saliban''' (''Salivan'') languages, also known as '''Piaroa–Saliban''' or '''Saliba–Piaroan''', are a small proposed [[language family]] of the middle [[Orinoco River|Orinoco Basin]], which forms an independent island within an area of [[Venezuela]] and [[Colombia]] (northern ''llanos'') dominated by peoples of [[Carib languages|Carib]] and [[Arawakan languages|Arawakan]] affiliation.
==Family division== A connection between the two primary divisions, Piaroan and Sáliba, is widely assumed but has not been demonstrated.<ref>Aikhenvald & Dixon, 1999, ''The Amazonian Languages''</ref> In addition, [[Hotï language|Hotï]] is "probably" related.<ref>Zent S & E Zent. 2008. Los Hoti, in Aborigenes de Venezuela, vol. 2, second edition [https://ivic.academia.edu/Zent/Papers/73523/Los_Jodi]</ref>
[[Saliba language|Saliba]] is a possible language isolate; if related to Piaroa, the connection is a distant one. Piaroan is a language or dialect cluster, consisting of [[Piaroa language|Piaroa]] itself, [[Wirö dialect|Wirö]] (or "Maco"), and the extinct [[Ature language|Ature]]. The Piaroa and Wirö both consider their languages to be distinct: they can understand each other, but not reliably.
Proposals have been put forth grouping the [[Hotï language]] (Jodï) with Piaroa–Saliban in a single [[Jodï–Saliban languages|Jodï–Saliban]] family.<ref> Labrada, Rosés; Emilio, Jorge (2015). [http://glottolog.org/resource/languoid/id/jodi1234 "Jodi-Saliban"]. ''[[Glottolog|Glottolog 2.7]]''. Jena: Max Planck Institute for the Science of Human History.</ref> Hotï was little known until recently and remains unclassified in most accounts.
