{{nofootnotes|date=August 2018}} {{Use Indian English|date=August 2018}} {{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}} {{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] --> | name = Ram Shri Mugali |image = |image_width = | caption = 25px | pseudonym = Rasika Ranga | birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1906|7|15}} | birth_place = Hole Alur, [[Gadag]] district, [[Karnataka]] | death_date = {{Death date|df=yes|1993|2|10}} | death_place = [[Bengaluru]], Karnataka | occupation = Professor, writer | nationality = Indian [[File:Flag of India.svg|15px]] | period = | genre = Fiction | subject = | awards = [[Sahitya Akademi award]] | movement = | signature = | website = }}
'''Ram Shri Mugali''' (Ranganatha Srinivasa Mugali) (15 July 1906 – 20 February 1993) was a notable writer in the [[Kannada language]]. He was awarded the prestigious central [[Sahitya Akademi award|Sahitya Akademi]] in 1956 for his work "Kannada Sahitya Charitre" in [[Kannada]]. Professor Mugali's nickname was ''Rasika Ranga'' ("Romantic Ranga"). He was the president of the 44th [[Kannada Sahitya Sammelana]] held in Siddganga, in the [[Tumkur]] district of Karnataka state, India.
==Early life == Mugali was born in Hole Alur in the [[Ron, Karnataka|Ron]] Taluk of [[Gadag district]], [[Karnataka]]. In 1933, he was appointed professor of Kannada at [[Willingdon College, Sangli]]. Notable among his students at Willingdon were [[Subbanna Ekkundi]] and [[Gangadhar V. Chittal]], who themselves would go on to become prominent writers in Kannada. The [[Jnanpith]] awardee [[V. K. Gokak]] was his peer at Willingdon college. In 1966, Mugali retired as a principal of the Willingdon College. From 1967 to 1970, he worked as the Head of the Kannada Department at the [[Bangalore University]], Bangalore. Mugali died in Bangalore on 20 February 1992.
